    'COASTAL_S07_CRIS_001' => [
        'briefing_json' => [
            'en' => [
                'situation'           => 'You are the Master of MV Med Tanker, a 4,500 DWT coastal product tanker (92 metres LOA, beam 14.6 metres, draft 6.3 metres) carrying 4,000 tonnes of gas oil (marine diesel, flash point 62°C) in six cargo tanks. You are 8 nautical miles southwest of Antalya port, proceeding at 10 knots on a course of 045°T toward the Antalya pilot boarding area. At 1045 local time the engine room fire alarm activated. The Chief Engineer immediately confirmed a fire — a fuel oil service line to the main engine has fractured at a flange joint, spraying pressurized fuel oil onto the hot exhaust manifold of the main engine. The fuel ignited and is burning fiercely around the main engine exhaust casing. The Chief Engineer and Second Engineer evacuated the engine room immediately and reported to the bridge. The engine room is now sealed, ventilation flaps closed. The main engine tripped automatically on the fire detection system — the vessel is now without propulsion and losing way. You have approximately 3-4 knots residual speed, decreasing. The wind is onshore SSW at 15 knots, and the current is setting NE at 0.8 knots — both are pushing the vessel toward the coast. At the current drift rate you estimate the vessel will be in water less than 20 metres deep in approximately 2 hours. The fire is contained within the engine room for now but the Chief Engineer reports that the fire is close to the generator fuel supply, and if it spreads, you will lose electrical power as well. The emergency generator on the upper deck is available. You have 12 crew members, all accounted for. The nearest vessel on AIS is a bulk carrier 3 nautical miles to the east, outbound from Antalya. The Turkish Coast Guard MRCC Antalya monitors VHF Channel 16.',
                'your_position'       => 'Wheelhouse, command. Chief Engineer and Second Engineer at the bridge reporting on the fire. Chief Officer at the fire control station on the main deck, preparing fire-fighting equipment. Bosun and two ABs standing by at the fire muster point. One AB at the helm (no steerage without engine, but ready for emergency rudder). Third Engineer checking the emergency generator.',
                'available_resources'  => 'Fixed CO2 fire-extinguishing system for engine room (87 cylinders, total flooding system), fire main with international shore connection, two fire pumps (one emergency pump on deck above engine room, powered by emergency generator), fire hoses and nozzles, fireman\'s outfits (2 sets), SCBA (4 sets), fire blankets. Emergency generator on upper deck (diesel, 120 kW — can power fire pump, navigation lights, radio, and essential systems). Steering gear — emergency hand-steering available. Two anchors, port anchor cleared. VHF radio on battery backup. EPIRB, SART, liferafts (2 × 20 persons). Lifeboat (1 × 20 persons). 12 crew total, all mustered. Cargo: 4,000t gas oil in 6 tanks, inerted cargo space. AIS showing bulk carrier 3 NM to east. MRCC Antalya on Ch 16.',
                'current_conditions'   => 'Fire in engine room — fuel oil on hot exhaust manifold, burning around main engine exhaust casing. Engine room sealed, ventilation closed. Main engine tripped — vessel without propulsion, losing way (3-4 knots decreasing). Wind SSW 15 knots onshore, current NE 0.8 knots — drift toward coast. Water depth decreasing: 2 hours to <20m depth. Fire near generator fuel supply — risk of blackout. Emergency generator available but not yet started. 12 crew mustered. Visibility good, sea state 2. Daylight. Bulk carrier 3 NM east. 8 NM from Antalya. Cargo: gas oil, flash point 62°C, tanks inerted.',
