        'briefing_json' => [
            'en' => [
                'situation'           => 'You are the Master of MV Izmir Bulk, a 5,000 DWT bulk coaster (88 metres LOA, beam 14.2 metres, draft 5.8 metres) carrying 4,200 tonnes of bagged cement from Izmir to Piraeus. You are in the central Aegean Sea, approximately 10 nautical miles east of Chios, heading south. The summer Meltemi wind has rapidly intensified beyond the forecast: current conditions are NW 35 knots with gusts to 42 knots, seas 4-5 metres with a short steep swell characteristic of the open Aegean. The vessel is experiencing heavy head seas (heading approximately 180°T into the NW swell) with pitching reaching 8-10 degrees and occasional green water over the bow. Your speed has dropped from the planned 12 knots to 7 knots due to the sea conditions, and the ETA to Piraeus has slipped from tomorrow morning (0800) to tomorrow evening (2000) — beyond the receiver\'s working hours. The delivery window in the charter party is 36 hours from now; if you arrive after that, a demurrage penalty of USD 4,000 per day applies. Your Chief Engineer has just reported that the sea water cooling pump for the main engine is showing increasing vibration — bearing wear suspected. The pump is still functional but he recommends reducing engine load to 75% as a precaution, which would reduce your speed through water to approximately 9 knots (but with the head seas, your effective speed over ground would be only 5 knots). Your vessel\'s CII rating is currently D — one more heavy-fuel voyage at high consumption and you risk falling to E rating, which requires a corrective action plan to the flag state. Running the engine hard into head seas dramatically increases fuel consumption. You have three options for shelter: Chios port (Greek, 10 NM to the west, good shelter, but requires Greek port entry procedures), Cesme (Turkish, 35 NM to the NE, familiar port, but requires backtracking), or continuing through the weather. The forecast shows the Meltemi moderating in 18-24 hours. Three of your 14 crew members are seasick and unable to perform duties effectively.',
